{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636599"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:30:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:30:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17593"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17593"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10307"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71552"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10307"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17593"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57043"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9996"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24099"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24118"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24145"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71552","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71552"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThere are various reflexes in the gastrointestinal tract which bring about luminal or sphincter activity. One is gastroileal reflex.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its action?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Contraction of the ileum in response to duodenal distension","Relaxation of the ileocaecal sphincter in response to gastric distension","Increased gastric motility in response to ileal distension","Relaxation of the lower oesophageal sphincter after eating","Contraction of the ileocaecal sphincter in response to colonic distension"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Erelaxation of the ileocaecal sphincter in response to gastric distension\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the gastroileal reflex. When food enters and distends the stomach, signals are sent via the enteric nervous system and the hormone gastrin to relax the ileocaecal sphincter. At the same time ileal peristaltic activity is increased. This allows ileal contents to move into the caecum, making room for the new food moving through the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContraction of the ileum in response to duodenal distension\u003C/strong\u003E - It is presence of food in the stomach, together with gastric peristalsis that initiates the gastroileal reflex\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERelaxation of the lower oesophageal sphincter after eating\u003C/strong\u003E - Food in the stomach would stimulate contraction of the lower oesophageal sphincter\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContraction of the ileocaecal sphincter in response to colonic distension\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the colonoileal reflex, which prevents retrograde flow\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased gastric motility in response to ileal distension\u003C/strong\u003E - This would be the opposite direction of normal gut reflexes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe gastroileal reflex is part of the coordinated movement of intestinal contents and helps maintain appropriate flow through the gastrointestinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The gastroileal reflex is triggered by food entering the stomach and causes relaxation of the ileocaecal sphincter.","This reflex facilitates movement of ileal contents into the caecum to accommodate incoming food from above.","The gastroileal reflex is mediated by the enteric nervous system and gastrin hormone."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021. Available from: https://clinicalkeymeded.elsevier.com/reader/books/9780323597128"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57043"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17593"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57043"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-19T11:27:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-19T11:28:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10307"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71552"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":